  "prompt": "Do I essentially have to be valedictorian to be accepted into an elite university like Stanford or Harvard?",
  "response": "No, you do not have to be valedictorian to be accepted into elite universities like Stanford or Harvard. While academic excellence is important, these universities use a holistic admissions process that considers many factors:\n\n1. Strong academic performance\n- High GPA\n- Challenging course load (AP, IB, honors classes)\n- Competitive test scores (SAT/ACT)\n\n2. Extracurricular activities\n- Leadership roles\n- Meaningful involvement\n- Depth of commitment\n\n3. Personal achievements\n- Awards and honors\n- Special talents\n- Unique accomplishments\n\n4. Essays and personal statements\n- Demonstrate character\n- Show passion and motivation\n- Highlight personal growth\n\n5. Recommendations\n- Strong letters from teachers\n- Perspectives on your abilities\n\n6. Diversity and personal background\n- Unique experiences\n- Overcoming challenges\n- Potential contributions to campus\n\nWhile being valedictorian can be impressive, these universities seek well-rounded students who demonstrate potential beyond just academic rankings. Many successful applicants are not #1 in their class but excel in other areas.\n\nEach application is reviewed individually, so focus on presenting your best, most authentic self.",
